<span id="freeTextContainer12272022288255620504">I don&apos;t think I can articulate how wonderful this book is without sounding corny. I cried. From happiness and melancholy and a deep, yet satisfying sadness. This is a remarkable story. Beyond remarkable. If only I could give it six stars. No review is going to do this book justice so just read it. Though, Janice Phelps Williams&apos; comes as close as one could possibly get. If you want to read it, go here: <a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='http://open.salon.com/blog/janicephelpswilliams/2011/05/04/the_story_of_beautiful_girl_by_rachel_simon'>http://open.salon.com/blog/janicephel...</a><br/><br/>I&apos;m just going to leave you with my favorite line from</span>
  <span id="freeText12272022288255620504" style="display:none">I don't think I can articulate how wonderful this book is without sounding corny. I cried. From happiness and melancholy and a deep, yet satisfying sadness. This is a remarkable story. Beyond remarkable. If only I could give it six stars. No review is going to do this book justice so just read it. Though, Janice Phelps Williams' comes as close as one could possibly get. If you want to read it, go here: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://open.salon.com/blog/janicephelpswilliams/2011/05/04/the_story_of_beautiful_girl_by_rachel_simon">http://open.salon.com/blog/janicephel...</a><br /><br />I'm just going to leave you with my favorite line from the book:<br /><br />"Each person must be in charge of their own drawing--period."</span>
