<div id="review_171139882" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/171139882" />
    <a title="Sally906" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4949011-sally906"><img alt="Sally906" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1621314070p2/4949011.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/171139882?book_show_action=true">May 25, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sally906" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sally906" href="/user/show/4949011-sally906">Sally906</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4949011-sally906?shelf=general-fiction">general-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer171139882" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9946636435106247713">At the end of THE STORY OF BEAUTIFUL GIRL author Rachel Simon explains what the inspirations were for the story. There were three main ones. Firstly her young sister Beth is mentally disabled; secondly as a young teen Rachel watched TV as a journalist exposed the WillowbrookStateSchool showing horrible images about the conditions of the people incarcerated there. These images shamed the nation and brought about reform for the intellectually disabled. Finally Rachel read a book written by Dave Ba</span>
  <span id="freeText9946636435106247713" style="display:none">At the end of THE STORY OF BEAUTIFUL GIRL author Rachel Simon explains what the inspirations were for the story. There were three main ones. Firstly her young sister Beth is mentally disabled; secondly as a young teen Rachel watched TV as a journalist exposed the WillowbrookStateSchool showing horrible images about the conditions of the people incarcerated there. These images shamed the nation and brought about reform for the intellectually disabled. Finally Rachel read a book written by Dave Bakke about a young African American teen found in an alley by police in 1945. This young man could not speak and gave hand signals that no-one understood. He was labelled ‘feebleminded’ and incarcerated in an institution where he was given a number as no one knew his name. There he stayed until his death 50 years later even though often concerned staff felt that he was very intelligent and just needed to be taught sign language. It was these three events that resulted in THE STORY OF BEAUTIFUL GIRL.<br /><br />In 1968, a retired teacher and widow named Martha is living alone in Pennsylvania when she answers a knock on her farmhouse door on a stormy night. On her doorstep are a young couple, Lynnie, a white woman with a developmental disability who has just given birth to a baby girl. Protecting Lynnie and the baby is Homan, a deaf African American man. It turns out that the two are escapees from the School for the Incurable and Feebleminded and the faculty heavies soon track the twosome down. Homan manages to escape but Lynnie is recaptured. What the school doesn’t know about though is the baby, and before she is taken away Lynnie whispers to Martha, "Hide her."<br /><br />Keeping her promise to Lynnie, Martha hides the baby, soon named Julia, with the help of various former students and raises Julia as her own granddaughter. So after the exciting coming together of the three main characters the rest of THE STORY OF BEAUTIFUL GIRL slows down and covers what happens over the next forty odd years as each of the characters go in separate directions. Martha leaves her home hiding the baby from the authorities. Homan moves around constantly trying to return to his ‘Beautiful Girl’ but being handicapped by not being able to speak or hear and Lynnie goes back to her old life at the institution with no means of escape.<br /><br />Each of the characters comes alive and blossoms as the story progresses Martha has her life completely turned around from one of loneliness to one of motherhood (ok grandmotherhood), love, friendships and travel. Lynnie has severe learning difficulties and was abandoned to the institution by her family when she was a child. She is a very frightened young woman at the start of the book, but is so brave in ensuring her daughter is safe and out of the system. Once the overhaul of the mental health system occurs Lynnie gets the help and training she needs and gradually blooms into a self supporting woman. Homan never ceases to long for Lynnie and the baby. Deaf since a childhood fever, he uses his mechanical skills to survive a series of adventures until he ends up in California and starts to amass a small fortune. By the time he is in a position to return to the school and rescue Lynnie the reformation has occurred and school has closed. He is unable to trace Lynnie through the records as Homan only knows her name to be ‘Beautiful Girl.’ Each of the characters struggle and sometimes they fail, but quite often circumstances fall into place and they succeed.<br /><br />Both captivating and heartbreaking I loved this thought provoking book. I loved the writing, I loved the uplifting love story, I loved the gentle progress of the characters and above all I loved the ending. When I read Rachel Simon’s reasons for writing the story it was all the more meaningful – I think she has done a good job in highlighting the terrible conditions of the mental health system without making it so harsh you can’t bear to read it.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9946636435106247713" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


